studyDesigns.name: Study Design
studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: LY900018 3 mg
arms.description: Single 3-mg dose of nasal glucagon (LY900018) administered by study site personnel.

arms.name: Intramuscular Glucagon 1 mg
arms.description: Single 1-mg dose of intramuscular glucagon (IMG, GlucaGen) administered by study site personnel.

studyCohorts.name: Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients with a diagnosis of Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus (T1DM).

studyCohorts.name: Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients with a diagnosis of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM).

eligibilityCriteria.name: Current enrollment in other clinical trials
Recent participation in other clinical trials
High total daily dose of insulin
History of severe hypoglycemia or loss of consciousness
History of epilepsy or seizure disorder

objectives.name: Primary Objective
objectives.text: To demonstrate that 3 mg LY900018 is non-inferior to 1 mg IMG for the proportion of patients achieving treatment success from insulin-induced hypoglycemia using a non-inferiority margin of 10%

objectives.name: Secondary Objective - Safety and Tolerability
objectives.text: To compare the safety and tolerability of 3 mg LY900018 with 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Secondary Objective - Pharmacokinetics
objectives.text: To characterize the PK profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Secondary Objective - Pharmacodynamics
objectives.text: To characterize the PD profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

endpoints.name: Primary Efficacy Endpoint
endpoints.text: The proportion of patients achieving treatment success defined as either an increase in PG to >70 mg/dL or an increase of >20 mg/dL from nadir within 30 minutes after administration of glucagon. The nadir is defined as the minimum PG value at the time of or within 10 minutes following glucagon administration.

endpoints.name: Safety and Tolerability Endpoints
endpoints.text: SAE, TEAEs (including gastrointestinal, nasal, and non-nasal AEs), vital signs

endpoints.name: Pharmacokinetic Endpoints
endpoints.text: PK parameters include AUC, Cmax, Tmax

endpoints.name: Pharmacodynamic Endpoints
endpoints.text: PD parameters include BGmax and Tmax

studyInterventions.name: LY900018
studyInterventions.description: Nasal glucagon (LY900018) is a powder formulation of human glucagon for the rescue treatment of hypoglycemia.

studyInterventions.name: GlucaGen
studyInterventions.description: Intramuscular glucagon (IMG) used as an active comparator.

studyInterventions.name: Human regular insulin
studyInterventions.description: Administered via IV infusion to induce hypoglycemia for the study procedure.

studyInterventions.name: IV glucose
studyInterventions.description: Administered if a patient's bedside plasma glucose concentration remains low after glucagon administration or if severe hypoglycemia symptoms occur.

notes.text: a. Samples for immunogenicity, should be collected every 12 weeks (847 days) until the titer returns to baseline (ie, returns to within a single 2-fold dilution of the baseline titer) or until 1 year after the last dose of study treatment. A time-matched PK (glucagon) sample may be collected at the follow-up immunogenicity assessment(s) if warranted and agreed upon between both the investigator and sponsor.

Note: If multiple procedures take place at the same time point, the following order of the procedure should be used: ECG, vital signs, and venipuncture. Plasma glucose sample should be collected as close as possible of protocol-specified time point.

administrations.name: Human regular insulin infusion
administrations.dose: 2 mU/kg/min, adjustable up to 3 mU/kg/min for T1DM or 4 mU/kg/min for T2DM
administrations.duration: Until bedside plasma glucose level is <60 mg/dL, for a maximum of 4 hours.

substances.description: A synthetic single-chain, 29-amino-acid polypeptide identical to human glucagon.

substances.description: Active substance used to induce hypoglycemia.

substances.description: Active substance in rescue medication for insufficient response to glucagon.

procedures.name: Insulin-induced Hypoglycemia
procedures.label: Hypoglycemia Induction
procedures.description: Procedure to induce hypoglycemia using an intravenous (IV) insulin infusion until plasma glucose level reaches <60 mg/dL.

procedures.name: Nasal Glucagon Administration
procedures.label: Nasal Glucagon Admin
procedures.description: Administration of 3 mg LY900018, a powder formulation of human glucagon, via a single-use nasal dosing device.

procedures.name: Intramuscular Glucagon Administration
procedures.label: IM Glucagon Admin
procedures.description: Administration of 1 mg reconstituted glucagon (GlucaGen) via intramuscular injection.

procedures.name: Venipuncture
procedures.label: Blood Draw
procedures.description: Collection of venous blood samples for laboratory analysis, including pharmacokinetics (PK), pharmacodynamics (PD), clinical chemistry, hematology, serology, HbA1c, and genetic analysis.

code.decode: Collection of venous blood by venipuncture

procedures.name: Urine Sample Collection
procedures.label: Urine Collection
procedures.description: Collection of urine samples for urinalysis, pregnancy testing, and drug screening.

procedures.name: Vital Signs Measurement
procedures.label: Vital Signs
procedures.description: Measurement of supine blood pressure, pulse rate, and body temperature at specified time points.

procedures.name: 12-lead Electrocardiogram
procedures.label: ECG
procedures.description: Recording of the heart's electrical activity using a single or triplicate 12-lead ECG.

code.decode: Electrocardiogram, routine ECG with at least 12 leads; with interpretation and report

procedures.name: Bedside Plasma Glucose Monitoring
procedures.label: Bedside PG Monitoring
procedures.description: Frequent monitoring of plasma glucose (PG) levels for safety during the hypoglycemia induction procedure and post-treatment.

procedures.name: Nasal Inspection
procedures.label: Nasal Inspection
procedures.description: Visual inspection of the nasal passages before and after study treatment administration.

procedures.name: Injection-Site Assessment
procedures.label: Injection Site Assessment
procedures.description: Assessment of the injection site for patients receiving intramuscular glucagon (IMG).

procedures.name: Height and Weight Measurement
procedures.label: Height and Weight
procedures.description: Measurement of patient's height at screening and weight before hypoglycemia induction.

procedures.name: Edinburgh Hypoglycemia Scale Assessment
procedures.label: Hypoglycemia Scale
procedures.description: Administration of the Edinburgh Hypoglycemia Scale questionnaire to evaluate recovery from clinical symptoms of hypoglycemia.

procedures.name: Intravenous Glucose Supplementation
procedures.label: IV Glucose Rescue
procedures.description: Administration of intravenous (IV) glucose as a rescue treatment if the patient experiences signs and symptoms of severe hypoglycemia requiring intervention.

medicalDevices.name: Nasal Dosing Device
medicalDevices.label: Nasal Glucagon Device
medicalDevices.description: A user-friendly, single-use, nasal dosing device that delivers 3 mg glucagon powder (LY900018) for absorption through the nasal mucosa.

medicalDevices.name: Continuous Subcutaneous Insulin Infusion Pump
medicalDevices.label: CSII Pump
medicalDevices.description: An insulin pump used by some patients for their daily insulin therapy.

medicalDevices.name: Syringe and Needle
medicalDevices.label: Syringe/Needle
medicalDevices.description: Implied device for reconstitution and intramuscular injection of GlucaGen.

medicalDevices.name: Bedside Glucose Meter
medicalDevices.label: Glucose Meter
medicalDevices.description: Implied device for bedside plasma glucose (PG) monitoring.

medicalDevices.name: Intravenous Infusion System
medicalDevices.label: IV System
medicalDevices.description: Implied system including an infusion pump for the administration of intravenous insulin.

conditions.name: Admission Rescheduling Condition
conditions.description: Condition for rescheduling admission to the CRU on Day 1.
conditions.text: Plasma Glucose (PG) level is not between 90 and 250 mg/dL on Day 1.

conditions.name: Stop Insulin Infusion Condition
conditions.description: Condition to stop the insulin infusion used to induce hypoglycemia.

conditions.name: TE ADA Positive Condition
conditions.text: Patient has treatment-emergent antidrug antibodies (TE ADA) at the follow-up/early discontinuation visit.

conditions.name: End of Additional Follow-up Criteria
conditions.description: Criteria to stop the additional follow-up for TE ADA.
conditions.text: Titer returns to baseline (within a single 2-fold dilution of the baseline titer) or 1 year has passed since the last dose of study treatment.

conditions.name: Interim Safety Review Trigger
conditions.description: A safety review is conducted after a specific number of patients complete Period 2.
conditions.text: Safety data will be reviewed after the first 6 patients are administered LY900018 in Period 2.

conditions.name: Study Continuation Post-Safety Review
conditions.description: Condition to continue dosing after the interim safety review.
conditions.text: No clinically significant safety findings for treatment or study procedure are noted in the first 6 patients.

conditions.name: Study Stopping Rule
conditions.description: The entire study may be stopped based on the interim safety review.
conditions.text: Study will be stopped if deemed necessary for patient safety following the review of safety data from the first 6 patients to complete Period 2 Day 1.

conditions.name: Patient Replacement Criteria
conditions.description: Condition for replacing a discontinued patient.
conditions.text: If patients discontinue from the study before completion of both periods with evaluable primary outcome for any reason, the patient may be replaced.

transitionRules.name: Screening to Treatment Transition
transitionRules.text: Eligible patients who have provided informed consent will be randomized on Day 1 of Period 1.

transitionRules.name: Period 1 to Period 2 Transition
transitionRules.text: After a washout period of 3 to 14 days, patients proceed from Period 1 to Period 2.

transitionRules.name: Transition to Additional Follow-up
transitionRules.text: Patients with TE ADA at follow-up/ED will undergo additional follow-up.

transitionRules.name: Handling of Inadvertently Enrolled Patients
transitionRules.text: If a patient did not meet enrollment criteria, documented approval from the sponsor is required for the patient to continue in the study.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Completion
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Completion of all protocol-required visits, including the final follow-up visit.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Discontinuation by Patient Decision
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The patient, or legal representative, requests to be withdrawn from the study.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Discontinuation by Investigator Decision
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The investigator decides that the patient should be discontinued from the study for any reason.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Discontinuation due to Other Study
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Enrollment in any other clinical study involving an investigational product or other incompatible medical research.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Discontinuation for Medical/Safety/Regulatory Reasons
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Participation needs to be stopped for medical, safety, regulatory, or other reasons consistent with applicable laws, regulations, and good clinical practice.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Lost to Follow-up
scheduleTimelineExits.description: A patient repeatedly fails to return for scheduled visits and is unable to be contacted by the study site.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Discontinuation for Safety
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The entire study is stopped for patient safety reasons based on the interim safety review of the first 6 patients.

commentAnnotations.text: Note to Regulatory Authorities: This document may contain protected personal data and/or commercially confidential information exempt from public disclosure. Eli Lilly and Company requests consultation regarding release/redaction prior to any public release. In the United States, this document is subject to Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Exemption 4 and may not be reproduced or otherwise disseminated without the written approval of Eli Lilly and Company or its subsidiaries.
Patients do not need to fast for samples at screening or follow-up. At Periods 1 and 2, samples should be collected from patients who have fasted at least 8 hours before any study procedures.
Serum pregnancy test will be performed at screening. Urine pregnancy test will be performed at every admission period and follow-up visit if applicable.
If a patient sneezes immediately after administration, document using the Nasal and Non-nasal Score Questionnaire (see Appendix 6 for a copy of the questionnaire).
If an SAE occurs after signing informed consent, but prior to receiving investigational product, AND is considered reasonably possibly related to a study procedure then it MUST be reported.

Pregnancy (maternal or paternal exposure to investigational product) does not meet the definition of an AE. However, to fulfill regulatory requirements any pregnancy should be reported following the SAE process to collect data on the outcome for both mother and fetus.
For the purposes of this study, an overdose of LY900018 or IMG is considered any dose that is higher than the assigned dose.
